{{Infobox software | name = Marble | logo = [[File:Marble-logo.svg|300px|Marble logo]] | screenshot = Marble Europe screenshot.png | screenshot size = 300px | caption = Screenshot of Marble showing Europe | developer = [[KDE]] | released = {{Start date and age|2006|11}} | latest release version = 2.2.0 (Part of KDE Applications 17.04) | latest release date = {{Start date and age|24|04|2017}} | programming language = [[C++]] ([[Qt (software)|Qt]]) | operating system = [[Unix-like]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] | language = Multiple languages | genre = [[Virtual globe]], [[route planning software]] | license = [[GNU LGPL]] | website = {{URL|http://marble.kde.org}} }} '''Marble''' is a [[virtual globe]] application which allows the user to choose among the Earth, the Moon, Venus, Mars and other planets to display as a 3-D model. It is [[free software]] under the terms of the [[GNU LGPL]], developed by [[KDE]] for use on [[personal computer]]s and [[smart phone]]s.<ref name="Marble Touch">{{cite web |url=http://nienhueser.de/blog/?p=352 |title=Introducing Marble Touch |last=Nienhüser |first=Dennis |publisher= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129025522/http://nienhueser.de/blog/?p=352 |archivedate=2011-11-29 |df= }}</ref> It is written in C++ and uses [[Qt (software)|Qt]].
Marble is intended to be very flexible; beyond its cross-platform design, the core components can easily be integrated into other programs. It is designed to run without the need for hardware acceleration, but it can be extended to use [[OpenGL]]. An important user-experience objective being that the application start fairly quickly, it ships with a minimal but useful off-line dataset (5–10MB{{Citation needed|reasom=Seems to be more than 20 MB|date=December 2013}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.kde.org/development/en/kdeedu/marble/introduction.html|title=Chapter 1. Introduction|publisher=[[KDE]]}}</ref>
Contributors have added support for on-line mapping sources such as [[OpenStreetMap]] and the ability to interpret [[Keyhole Markup Language|KML]] files. Marble also provides [[Route planning software|route planning]] capabilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nienhueser.de/blog/?p=137 |title=Worldwide and Offline Routing |last=Nienhüser |first=Dennis |publisher=Nienhueser.de |date=2010-07-24 |accessdate=2010-10-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729005700/http://nienhueser.de/blog/?p=137 |archivedate=2010-07-29 |df= }}</ref> A [[GPS navigation software|navigation mode]] called MarbleToGo was developed as part of [[Google Summer of Code|Google Summer of Code 2010]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://socghop.appspot.com/gsoc/student_project/show/google/gsoc2010/kde/t127230760808 |title=Show Student Project |publisher=[[Google]] |date= |accessdate=2010-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://siddharthgsoc.blogspot.com/ |title=GSoC: MarbleToGo (Navigation Mode) |last=Srivastava |first=Siddharth |publisher=[[Blogspot]] |date= |accessdate=2010-10-25}}</ref> It was later partially rewritten and renamed to ''Marble Touch''.<ref name="Marble Touch" />
''Geothek'' is a [[Fork (software development)|fork]] of Marble adding a statistics module, pixel maps, and a 3D view. It is developed and used by Austrian publisher [[Ed. Hölzel]] as atlas software for classrooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.kde.org/2010/08/07/look-geothek-11-digital-world-atlas |title=A look at Geothek 1.1 Digital World Atlas |date=2010-08-07}}</ref>
