[[Image:Negroland and Guinea with the European Settlements, 1736.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Map by [[Herman Moll]], London, 1729, showing the Grain Coast]]
'''Pepper Coast''' was the name given by European traders to a coastal area of western [[Africa]], between [[Cape Mesurado]] and [[Cape Palmas]]. It encloses the present republic of [[Liberia]]. It got its name from the [[grain of paradise|melegueta pepper]]. The pepper is also known as the ''grain of paradise'', which gave rise to an alternative name, the '''Grain Coast'''. The importance of the spice is shown by the designation of the area from the [[Saint John River (Liberia)|Saint John River]] (at present-day [[Buchanan, Liberia|Buchanan]]) to Harper in Liberia as the "Grain Coast" in reference to the availability of grains of paradise.<ref name="Laurie">''Laurie's Sailing Directory for the Ethiopic or Southern Atlantic Ocean to the Rio de la Plata, Cape Horn, and the Cape of Good Hope etc., including the Islands between the two coasts''; 4th Edition 1855</ref> In some cases (as shown on the map) this term covers a wider area incorporating [[Sierra Leone]] and the [[Ivory Coast]].

