{{DEFAULTSORT:Radevina}} [[Category:Geographical regions of Serbia]]

List of '''[[Red Star Belgrade]]'s official European matches''' from 1956 till today.<ref>http://kassiesa.nl/uefa/clubs/search/fm.php?search=red+star</ref>
==A brief history== Red Star's European story began in 1956 in [[Kerkrade]], Netherlands. The first rival in the first round of the [[1956–57 European Cup]] were Dutch champions [[Roda JC Kerkrade|Rapid JC]] (the club later change its name to Roda JC), with [[Bora Kostić]] scoring Red Star's first ever European goal. Since the first [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] semi-final, when Red Star was eliminated by [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], Red Star participated 14 times in a European competition quarter-final (not counting the [[Mitropa Cup]]), and was a semi-finalist in each of the three cup competitions for a total of six appearances. Throughout this time, Red Star steadily kept its place among the top 15 European clubs on [[UEFA]]'s ranking list, situated just behind [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] for the number of participations in European Cups.<ref>[http://www.crvenazvezdafk.com/en/istorija2.htm crvenazvezdafk.com - Autumn]</ref> In 1991, Red Star were finally ready for Europe and the road to [[Bari]], where the final of the [[1991 European Cup Final|1991 European Cup]] was played.
From 1992 to 1995, the clubs from FR Yugoslavia were forbidden to take part in the European competitions, due to the [[sanctions against Yugoslavia]]. Red Star has never managed to regain its previous reputation afterwards, participating in the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup/UEFA Europa League]] group stage for three times since 1995 and qualify for the [[UEFA Champions League]] group stage one time [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League|2018–19]].
